Google faces investigation over 'exclusive deals'
Brussels' antitrust watchdog is considering claims that Google made anti-competitive deals to promote Android Google's famous logo By Olivia Goldhill
12:03PM BST 14 Jun 2013
Follow Comments
Allegations include concerns that Google offered cut price licensing for the Android platform's open-source software to phone manufacturers, and benefited from exclusivity deals. According to documents seen by the Financial Times, the Brussels antitrust watchdog will look at “potential requests by Google to cancel and/or delay the launch of smartphone devices” in response to competing operating systems. The informal investigation, which is in an early stage, follows complaints in April from 14 companies, including Microsoft and Nokia, to the European Commission that Google was using “deceptive conduct to lock out competition in mobile”. Google's success in online mobile services such as search and Maps is partly owed to mobile phone manufacturers using Android as a platform. Devices with Android software made up 74 per cent of global smartphone sales in the first quarter, according to Gartner. Brussels's investigation into Android has been open for more than a year but the commission sent out a 23-page questionnaire on mobile operating systems and pre-installed services after Google's rival companies lodged the formal complaint. The questionnaire does not necessarily mean the commission will launch a formal investigation of Google's sales. Related Articles
