Joaquín Almunia, the EU’s competition chief, has not said the questionnaire and informal Android investigation are linked, but there is overlap between the complainants in both cases. A proposed antitrust settlement earlier this year from the EU competition commissioner on Google's search business has been criticised by rivals as having too many loopholes to be effective. The commission, which has the power to impose 10 per cent fines on global turnover, has said it will negotiate improvements on the settlement in the coming months but declined to comment on the questionnaire. Google said: “Android is an open platform that fosters competition. Handset makers, carriers and consumers can decide how to use Android, including which applications they want to use.”
